title: Fix ROI Pooling bin size calculation

labels.name: status:wontfix
labels.description: This will not be worked on

body:
**Description**: Improve ROI Pooling bin size calculation by doing integer flooring/ceiling instead of float flooring/ceiling.

**Motivation and Context**
- Why is this change required? What problem does it solve?

Even if an integer is a multiple of another integer, dividing them together after converting them to floats is not guaranteed to give a number representable by an integer. For example, `4.00000 / 2.00000` could give `2.00000` or `1.99994` depending on the architecture (e.g. x64 vs ARM) or other factors. This is especially a problem here because of `floor` and `ceil`, which can give 2 completely different indices depending on the result of the division. `floor(2.00000) == 2.00000`, but `floor(1.99994) == 1.00000`.

Since all operands of the division before `ceil` and `floor` are positive integers, we can do integer flooring and ceiling instead of converting them to float beforehand. This will give more precise results, and most importantly consistent results. We don't have to do any float arithmetic during this operation.

title: flatten conv2d when input_width==kernel_width
body:
**Description**: 
This change implements a NCHWc optimization for the case input_width==kernel_width. These operations can be flattened to effectively a 1D convolution using striding to allow the NCHWc kernels to better process data.

**Motivation and Context**
This change addresses a performance bug seen in some internal non-image models using convolution using the above properties. The NCHW MlasConv detected this pattern and converted the convolution to a simple GEMM call. With this fix, models run with the NCHWc optimizer enabled run at the same speed as with "-o 2".

The existing MLAS unit test already covers the new code path for NCHWc thanks to reusing parts of the NCHW tests.

title: Strip invalid dim_param and dim_value values out. Allow re-use in event of shape mismatch if buffer is large enough
body:
**Description**: 
Remove known invalid values from dim_param and dim_value. 
Treats the removed values as unknown which allows shape inferencing to fill them in where possible.
Allow re-use of a buffer if there's a shape mismatch and the buffer is large enough.

**Motivation and Context**
Allows existing models that have invalid dim_value and dim_param values set by converters to still run. 
Maintains preventing buffer overflow errors which may silently fail and lead to invalid results.
Warns if there's a shape mismatch which most likely indicates a bad model which is only able to run by chance (50% of the time a shape mismatch will result in a failed attempt to re-use a buffer that is too small)

title: Use TensorRT engine as CUDA kernel to remove memory copy
body:
This PR is to remove memory copy between TensorRT and CUDA.

Current TensorRT execution provider is used as a CPU device. When a graph is partitioned between TensorRT and CUDA execution providers, memory copy occurs. The overhead will be significant if there are many partitions in the graph. 
An easy way to remove the memory copy is to treat TensorRT as a compiled CUDA kernel. The kernel will get inputs from (put outputs to) allocated CUDA memories so no memory copy is needed. Also the kernel will use the same CUDA stream and no steam sync is needed.

title: How to build and use onnxruntime static lib on windows?
body:
Use build flag  --build_shared_lib, we can get onnxruntime.lib, onnxruntime.dll, which can  be dynamically linked,
While how to build a single onnxruntime static lib like onnxruntime.lib for  static link?

I had tried to change the following code in  onnxruntime.cmake  to get a single onnxruntime.libbut it can't be resolve when used in vs2017, I  cannot figure out why, can someone meet the same issue?

 add_library(onnxruntime SHARED ${onnxruntime_session_srcs})
=>
 add_library(onnxruntime STATIC ${onnxruntime_session_srcs})
and use flag --build_shared_lib to trigger the  onnxruntime.cmake build

title: Question: How can I retrieve the metadata denotations from any onnx model in Android?
body:
Hi all,
I'm not very familiar with compiling c/c++ and using ndk for android. For a few weeks I have been busy trying to make onnx_proto and protobuf functions work on android next to onnxruntime (onnxruntime_session). Ultimately I'd like to automatically detect the type of model, input and output data structure to be able to pick different models (say object detection) and automatically pre-process the available data to fit the model. The metadata I can retrieve from the functions in onnxruntime session and I am able to run onnx models if I know the but to get the denotations, if i'm correct, I will need protobuf and onnx_proto functions. I wanted to use something like the following code.

```c++
#include "onnx/onnx.pb.h"
#include <fstream>
#include <iostream>
#include <string>
onnx::ModelProto model;
std::ifstream in("den_ImageNet.onnx", std::ios_base::binary);
model.ParseFromIstream(&in);
in.close();
onnx::StringStringEntryProto metadata;
metadata = model.metadata_props(0);
std::cout << metadata.key() << " " <<metadata.value() << "\n";
```
This code works on my Ubuntu installation but I am not even able to declare a ModelProto in Android Studio. 

I'd like to ask you if this is feasible within the onnxruntime sources. I have tried to include the libonnx_proto.a/.so, libprotobuf.a/so (I compiled them into shared and static libraries) but it all doesn't seem to work.

**Describe the bug**

Do not provide an axes attribute when using the squeeze operator.

**Expected behavior**
When the axes attribute is not provided, all single dimensions should be removed from the shape as specified in the documentation and there should be no error asking the axes attribute to be set.

Dupe of #1491

title: Optimize Fence checking performance
body:
**Description**: Describe your changes.
- For majority of nodes, we do not need to do fence check. Instead, we only need to do FenceCheck for  CPU<->GPU mem sync node
- But we pay the Fence check cost for every single node and every single input and output.

This change will minimize the Fence check to only do it when necessary.

**Motivation and Context**
- Why is this change required? What problem does it solve?
Perf profiling on light weight models shows that Fence check has significant overhead. This overhead can be minimized.
- If it fixes an open issue, please link to the issue here.
Epic 479465

title: Fix buffer overrun bug in CPU upsample op
body:
**Description**: 
Fix buffer overrun bug in CPU upsample op. Introduced in #1484
**Motivation and Context**
- Why is this change required? What problem does it solve?
A buffer overrun bug may cause application crash. (wrote more bytes than the buffer has)

- If it fixes an open issue, please link to the issue here.

title: Rename Tensor.Size() to Tensor.SizeInBytes()
body:
**Description**: Describe your changes.
Tensor.Size() returns its memory size in bytes instead of element size. The name is confusing. Rename it to SizeInBytes() 
**Motivation and Context**
- Why is this change required? What problem does it solve?
- If it fixes an open issue, please link to the issue here.

title: Profiler-IsEnabled
body:
**Description**: Avoid use of Hungarian naming convention for cross-platform API names.

**Motivation and Context**

I'm taking my cue here from the "ONNX Runtime coding conventions and standard" document which say we use the "Google C++ style guide", and that says "Do not use Hungarian notation"

https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/master/docs/Coding_Conventions_and_Standards.md

https://google.github.io/styleguide/cppguide.html#Windows_Code

X-ref: internal PR 4824

title: Organized build instructions
body:
**Description**: 
- Organized the build instructions into different devices.
- Added building the shared library. 

**Motivation and Context**
- Makes navigating the instructions easier and friendlier.

title: Support missing optional attribute in Squeeze operator
body:
**Description**: 
`Squeeze` operator supports cases where the `axes` attribute may be missing (as the attribute is optional per spec). This change removes that the strict enforcement that the optional attribute be present.

**Motivation and Context**
Resolve #1496

title: Enable float16 MatMul+Add -> GEMM fusion for performance boost
body:
**Description**:
Enable float16 MatMul+Add -> GEMM fusion, which is currently blocked by a slightly too restrictive type check. The fusion does actually work correctly with float16 on both DirectML GPU and CPU with the check loosened.

**Motivation and Context**
- The current 'if' check misses a measurable perf improvement opportunity for float16 models such as EmotionFerPlus. This perf issue was brought up by an external IHV while profiling on their hardware.
- This is tested against our ONNX conformance suite and WinML model zoo.
- https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/1494 (related OS bug #22555607)

title: Bug fix for shape of optional output in Dropout op
body:
**Description**: 
Dropout op produces an output 'mask' (optionally).This change is to fix the shape of the output if generated.

As part of this change, bring Dropout kernels declared for CUDA on parity with their CPU equivalent (needed for new tests to pass)

CC: @fdwr 

**Motivation and Context**
Resolve #1487

title: Fix regression with empty quote
body:
Empty double quote `""` is passed to `find_package(Thread)`, causing a test command `gcc ... "" ...` failed while trying to compile a source file with empty name.

```
[user@******** /]# gcc ""
gcc: error: : No such file or directory
gcc: fatal error: no input files
compilation terminated.
```

This fixed the "Thread not found" issue in https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/pull/1469

title: GENERAL ERROR : Non-zero status code returned while running Node: concat_35 Status Message:

concat.cc:47 onnxruntime::ConcatBase::PrepareForComputeNon concat axis dimensions must match: Axis 0 has mismatched dimensions of 1 and 16

My code is as follows:
```
import onnxruntime as ort


testX, testY=load_data("test")
sess = ort.InferenceSession("TextRCNN.onnx")
for input_meta in sess.get_inputs():
    print(input_meta)
for output_meta in sess.get_outputs():
    print(output_meta)

for input in testX:
    feed_data={"input_x:0":np.array([input], dtype=np.int32)}
    result = sess.run(["predictions:0"], feed_data)

```
NodeArg(name='input_x:0', type='tensor(int32)', shape=[None, 36])
